Bassil entered the game & quot; the street & quot ;: Aouni trend .. & quot; I'm not alone & quot;
04 Nov 2019, 06:42 by Lebanon 24
Leah al-Azzi wrote in Al-Akhbar: Gibran Bassil wanted to enter the street game, and to assure that he was still able to mobilize the FPM. The Aouni people went yesterday to thousands to Baabda to demonstrate near the presidential palace in support of the era. Basil succeeded, though his speech showed no change in his political behavior. He wants to put himself in the ranks of the opposition, without taking off the dress of power. The Free Patriotic Movement decided yesterday to move its "street" to convey a message that "I am not alone." It is true that the crowd, which was assigned a patch of not more than one word, was not hundreds of thousands and can not be compared to the number that participated in the inauguration of Michel Aoun, but it is recorded to the Aounis enable them to mobilize a large part of their street in these circumstances. The occasion of the passage of the half-term of the presidential term was the "optimal" time to respond to the slogans of the majority of the protesters in the past 20 days. The October 17 uprising, though triggered by the government's economic policies and the worsening financial situation, is largely a slogan of political slogans directed against Gibran Bassil and the presidential era. They are theoretically more "affected" than the street. The story is not only about the possibility of a "political direction" against the Aounist movement, but it also bears part of the responsibility that justifies the resentment of the people, after the result of the "Covenant" in the first three years, "disappointing", and does not meet the high expectations that were met On his shoulders. Many promises did not find their way into implementation, always on the pretext that others "obstructed our work", whether before or after taking office. Yesterday, Bassil added to the "obstruction", a new equation that the "current" is being wronged twice: "once the symbols of corruption, and once the victims of corruption." The party, which says it is most represented in its "environment", has the largest parliamentary bloc, and a third of the guarantors in the cabinet (before the resignation of the government), insists to keep itself in the circle of defense and weakness. From 1990 to 2005, "we exiled, isolated, persecuted, and practiced all policies of waste, looting and corruption." After entering the state, "we started a struggle against corruption." To read the full article click here
